    Is GitHub free?
    An AI Overview is not available for this searchCan't generate an AI overview right now. Try again later.
    AI Overview
    Yes, GitHub is free for most personal and team use cases, offering core features for unlimited public repositories and a free tier for private repositories with a limited feature set. Paid plans are available for more advanced features, such as enhanced security, administrative controls, and full feature sets for private repositories. 
    Free features
    • For personal accounts:
      • Unlimited collaborators on unlimited public and private repositories. 
      • Limited features on private repositories, such as access to a basic feature set. 
    • For organizations:
      • Unlimited collaborators on unlimited public repositories with a full feature set. 
      • Unlimited collaborators on unlimited private repositories with a limited feature set. 
      • Can be used for free with limited features on private repositories. 
    • Core features:
      • Version control, code review, issue tracking, and project management are available for free. 
      • The core GitHub features are free for everyone as of April 2020. 
      • Free hosting of static websites using GitHub Pages. 
    Paid features
    • GitHub Pro:
      Includes GitHub Support via email, in addition to the free personal account features. 
    • GitHub Team:
      Includes additional features for organizations, such as enhanced security, SAML single sign-on, and improved support coverage. 
    • GitHub Enterprise:
      Offers both cloud-hosted and self-hosted options with the most advanced security and administrative features.

      Who owns GitHub?
      An AI Overview is not available for this searchCan't generate an AI overview right now. Try again later.
      AI Overview
      Microsoft owns GitHub. The company acquired the developer platform for $7.5 billion in 2018. Although now a subsidiary of Microsoft, GitHub largely operates as an independent entity. 
      • Acquisition: Microsoft acquired GitHub in 2018. 
      • Deal terms: The acquisition was valued at $7.5 billion in Microsoft stock. 
      • Structure: GitHub continues to operate with a degree of independence under Microsoft's ownership.
